'''Spar and Membrane Structure''' (SMS) is a type of wall construction in which lightly reinforced 2" - 3" [5&nbsp;cm - 8&nbsp;cm] of [[shotcrete]] or [[gunite]] skins (membranes) are interconnected with extended “X” shaped light [[rebar]] (spars) through the interior of the wall. Typically, SMS construction uses straw bales as leave in [[formwork]] for the concrete skins with the spars placed at the head of each bale, however, many other types of formwork could be used in place of straw bales. The SMS system was invented and patented by R. Gary Black, an [[engineer]] and professor of [[architecture]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>Black, Gary, and Mannik, Henri, “Spar and Membrane Structure” The Last Straw journal, #17, Winter 1997</ref>

